  <section class=3D"informative" id=3D"the-model-sources-sinks-constraints-=
and-settings" data-cite=3D"?webrtc"><!--OddPage--><div class=3D"header-wrap=
per"><h2 id=3D"x5-the-model-sources-sinks-constraints-and-settings"><bdi cl=
ass=3D"secno">5.<!---0.032930%--> </bdi>The model: sources, sinks, constrai=
nts, and settings</h2><a class=3D"self-link" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/=
mediacapture-main/#the-model-sources-sinks-constraints-and-settings" aria-l=
abel=3D"Permalink for Section 5."></a></div><p><em>This section is non-norm=
ative.<!---0.032930%--></em></p>
   =20
    <p><a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/=
mediacapture-main/#dfn-user-agent" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-=
user-agent-42">User Agents<!---0.032930%--></a> provide a media pipeline fr=
om sources to sinks. In a <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"htt=
ps://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-user-agent" class=3D"internalDFN"=
 id=3D"ref-for-dfn-user-agent-43">User Agent<!---0.032930%--></a>,
    sinks are the &lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data-link-type=3D=
"element" data-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/embedded-content.html" data=
-cite-frag=3D"the-img-element" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipa=
ge/embedded-content.html#the-img-element">img<!---0.032930%--></a></code>&g=
t;, &lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data-link-type=3D"element" data=
-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/media.html" data-cite-frag=3D"video" href=
=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.html#video">video<!---0.03=
2930%--></a></code>&gt;, and &lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data-l=
ink-type=3D"element" data-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/media.html" data=
-cite-frag=3D"audio" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.h=
tml#audio">audio<!---0.032930%--></a></code>&gt; tags.
    Traditional sources include streamed content, files, and web resources.=
 The
    media produced by these sources typically does not change over time - t=
hese
    sources can be considered to be static.</p>
    <p>The sinks that display these sources to the user (the actual tags
    themselves) have a variety of controls for manipulating the source cont=
ent.
    For example, an &lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data-link-type=
=3D"element" data-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/embedded-content.html" d=
ata-cite-frag=3D"the-img-element" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/mult=
ipage/embedded-content.html#the-img-element">img<!---0.032930%--></a></code=
>&gt; tag scales down a huge source image of
    1600x1200 pixels to fit in a rectangle defined with
    <code>width=3D"400"</code> and <code>height=3D"300"</code>.</p>
    <p>Sources have a lifetime. By default, a source lifetime is tied
    to the context that created it. For instance, sources created
    by <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"idl" data-lt=3D"MediaD=
evices" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dom-mediadevices" =
class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dom-mediadevices-3"><code>MediaDevices<=
!---0.032930%--></code></a>.<!---0.032930%--><a data-link-type=3D"idl" data=
-xref-type=3D"method" data-link-for=3D"MediaDevices" data-xref-for=3D"Media=
Devices" data-lt=3D"getUserMedia()" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapt=
ure-main/#dom-mediadevices-getusermedia" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-fo=
r-dom-mediadevices-getusermedia-12"><code>getUserMedia<!---0.032930%--></co=
de></a><code>(<!---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%-->)</code><!=
---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%--> are considered as created
    by its navigator.<a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"idl" dat=
a-lt=3D"mediaDevices" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dom-=
mediadevices" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dom-mediadevices-4"><code=
>mediaDevices<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---0.032930%--> context.
    Similarly, sources of <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"int=
erface" data-lt=3D"RTCRtpReceiver" data-cite=3D"webrtc" data-cite-path=3D""=
 data-cite-frag=3D"dom-rtcrtpreceiver" href=3D"https://www.w3.org/TR/webrtc=
/#dom-rtcrtpreceiver"><code>RTCRtpReceiver<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---=
0.032930%--> objects are bound
    to the <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"interface" data-lt=
=3D"RTCPeerConnection" data-cite=3D"webrtc" data-cite-path=3D"" data-cite-f=
rag=3D"dom-rtcpeerconnection" href=3D"https://www.w3.org/TR/webrtc/#dom-rtc=
peerconnection"><code>RTCPeerConnection<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---0.0=
32930%--> itself, which is bound to its creation context.
    Except if stated explicitly in the definition of specific sources,
    a source is always <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" data-link-for=
=3D"source" data-xref-for=3D"source" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacap=
ture-main/#source-stopped" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-source-stopp=
ed-5">stopped<!---0.032930%--></a> when its creation context goes away.
    It should be noted that two sources of different contexts
    may use the same capture device at the same time.
    One source can be stopped independently of the other one.
    </p>
    <p>The getUserMedia API adds dynamic sources such as microphones and
    cameras - the characteristics of these sources can change in response t=
o
    application needs. These sources can be considered to be dynamic in nat=
ure.
    A &lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data-link-type=3D"element" da=
ta-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/media.html" data-cite-frag=3D"video" hr=
ef=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.html#video">video<!---0.=
032930%--></a></code>&gt; element that displays media from a dynamic source=
 can
    either perform scaling or it can feed back information along the media
    pipeline and have the source produce content more suitable for display.=
</p>
    <div class=3D"note" role=3D"note" id=3D"issue-container-generatedID-10"=
><div role=3D"heading" class=3D"note-title marker" id=3D"h-note-10" aria-le=
vel=3D"3"><span>Note</span><!---0.032930%--></div><div class=3D"">
      <p><strong>Note:</strong> This sort of feedback loop is obviously jus=
t
      enabling an "optimization", but it's a non-trivial gain. This
      optimization can save battery, allow for less network congestion,
      etc...</p>
    </div></div>
    <p>Note that <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"idl" data-lt=
=3D"MediaStream" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dom-media=
stream" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dom-mediastream-56"><code>Media=
Stream<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---0.032930%--> sinks (such as
    &lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data-link-type=3D"element" data=
-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/media.html" data-cite-frag=3D"video" href=
=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.html#video">video<!---0.03=
2930%--></a></code>&gt;, &lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data-link-=
type=3D"element" data-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/media.html" data-cit=
e-frag=3D"audio" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.html#=
audio">audio<!---0.032930%--></a></code>&gt;, and even
    <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"interface" data-lt=3D"RTC=
PeerConnection" data-cite=3D"webrtc" data-cite-path=3D"" data-cite-frag=3D"=
dom-rtcpeerconnection" href=3D"https://www.w3.org/TR/webrtc/#dom-rtcpeercon=
nection"><code>RTCPeerConnection<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---0.032930%-=
->) will continue to have mechanisms to further
    transform the source stream beyond that which the <a href=3D"https://w3=
c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-settings" class=3D"internalDFN" data-lin=
k-type=3D"dfn" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-settings-3">Settings</a>,
    <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-capabilities" c=
lass=3D"internalDFN" data-link-type=3D"dfn" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-capabilities-=
4">Capabilities</a>, and <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main=
/#dom-constraints" class=3D"internalDFN" data-link-type=3D"idl" id=3D"ref-f=
or-dom-constraints-2"><code>Constraints</code></a> described in this specif=
ication
    offer. (The sink transformation options, including those of
    <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"interface" data-lt=3D"RTC=
PeerConnection" data-cite=3D"webrtc" data-cite-path=3D"" data-cite-frag=3D"=
dom-rtcpeerconnection" href=3D"https://www.w3.org/TR/webrtc/#dom-rtcpeercon=
nection"><code>RTCPeerConnection<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---0.032930%-=
->, are outside the scope of this
    specification.)</p>
    <p>The act of changing or applying a track constraint may affect the
    <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/med=
iacapture-main/#dfn-settings" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-setti=
ngs-4">settings<!---0.032930%--></a> of all tracks sharing that source and
    consequently all down-level sinks that are using that source. Many sink=
s
    may be able to take these changes in stride, such as the
    <code>&lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data-link-type=3D"element=
" data-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/media.html" data-cite-frag=3D"video=
" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.html#video">video<!-=
--0.032930%--></a></code>&gt;</code> element or <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_"=
 data-link-type=3D"interface" data-lt=3D"RTCPeerConnection" data-cite=3D"we=
brtc" data-cite-path=3D"" data-cite-frag=3D"dom-rtcpeerconnection" href=3D"=
https://www.w3.org/TR/webrtc/#dom-rtcpeerconnection"><code>RTCPeerConnectio=
n<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---0.032930%-->.
    Others like the Recorder API may fail as a result of a source setting
    change.</p>
    <p>The <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"interface" data-lt=
=3D"RTCPeerConnection" data-cite=3D"webrtc" data-cite-path=3D"" data-cite-f=
rag=3D"dom-rtcpeerconnection" href=3D"https://www.w3.org/TR/webrtc/#dom-rtc=
peerconnection"><code>RTCPeerConnection<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---0.0=
32930%--> is an interesting object because it
    acts simultaneously as both a sink <strong>and</strong> a source for
    over-the-network streams. As a sink, it has source transformational
    capabilities (e.g., lowering bit-rates, scaling-up / down resolutions, =
and
    adjusting frame-rates), and as a source it could have its own settings
    changed by a track source.</p>
    <p>To illustrate how changes to a given source impact various sinks,
    consider the following example. This example only uses width and height=
,
    but the same principles apply to all of the <a href=3D"https://w3c.gith=
ub.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-settings" class=3D"internalDFN" data-link-type=
=3D"dfn" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-settings-5">Settings</a> exposed in this
    specification. In the first figure a home client has obtained a video
    source from its local video camera. The source's width and height setti=
ngs
    are 800 pixels and 600 pixels, respectively. Three
    <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"idl" data-lt=3D"MediaStre=
am" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dom-mediastream" class=
=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dom-mediastream-57"><code>MediaStream<!---0.=
032930%--></code></a><!---0.032930%--> objects on the home client contain t=
racks
    that use this same &lt;<!---0.032930%--><a data-link-type=3D"idl" data-=
xref-type=3D"attribute|dict-member|const" data-link-for=3D"MediaStreamTrack=
" data-xref-for=3D"MediaStreamTrack" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacap=
ture-main/#dfn-deviceid" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-deviceid-1=
"><code>deviceId<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---0.032930%-->. The three me=
dia streams
    are connected to three different sinks: a <code>&lt;<code><a data-xref-=
type=3D"element" data-link-type=3D"element" data-cite=3D"html" data-cite-pa=
th=3D"/media.html" data-cite-frag=3D"video" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatw=
g.org/multipage/media.html#video">video<!---0.032930%--></a></code>&gt;</co=
de>
    element (A), another <code>&lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data=
-link-type=3D"element" data-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/media.html" da=
ta-cite-frag=3D"video" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media=
.html#video">video<!---0.032930%--></a></code>&gt;</code> element (B), and =
a peer
    connection (C). The peer connection is streaming the source video to a
    remote client. On the remote client there are two media streams with tr=
acks
    that use the peer connection as a source. These two media streams are
    connected to two <code>&lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"element" data-lin=
k-type=3D"element" data-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/media.html" data-c=
ite-frag=3D"video" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/media.htm=
l#video">video<!---0.032930%--></a></code>&gt;</code> element sinks (Y and
    Z).</p><img alt=3D"Changing media stream source effects: before the req=
uested change" src=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/images/change=
_states_before.svg" width=3D"800" height=3D"342">
    <p>Note that at this moment, all of the sinks on the home client must a=
pply
    a transformation to the original source's provided dimension settings. =
B is
    scaling the video down, A is scaling the video up (resulting in loss of
    quality), and C is also scaling the video up slightly for sending over =
the
    network. On the remote client, sink Y is scaling the video <em>way</em>
    down, while sink Z is not applying any scaling.</p>
    <p>In response to <!---0.032930%--><a data-link-type=3D"idl" data-xref-=
type=3D"method" data-link-for=3D"MediaStreamTrack" data-xref-for=3D"MediaSt=
reamTrack" data-lt=3D"applyConstraints()" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/med=
iacapture-main/#dom-mediastreamtrack-applyconstraints" class=3D"internalDFN=
" id=3D"ref-for-dom-mediastreamtrack-applyconstraints-5"><code>applyConstra=
ints<!---0.032930%--></code></a><code>(<!---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%--><!=
---0.032930%-->)</code><!---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%--> being called, one=
 of the
    tracks wants a higher resolution (1920 by 1200 pixels) from the home
    client's video source.</p><img alt=3D"Changing media stream source effe=
cts: after the requested change" src=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-=
main/images/change_states_after.svg" width=3D"800" height=3D"344">
    <p>Note that the source change immediately affects all of the tracks an=
d
    sinks on the home client, but does not impact any of the sinks (or sour=
ces)
    on the remote client. With the increase in the home client source video=
's
    dimensions, sink A no longer has to perform any scaling, while sink B m=
ust
    scale down even further than before. Sink C (the peer connection) must =
now
    scale down the video in order to keep the transmission constant to the
    remote client.</p>
    <p>While not shown, an equally valid settings change request could be m=
ade
    on the remote client's side. In addition to impacting sink Y and Z in t=
he
    same manner as A, B and C were impacted earlier, it could lead to
    re-negotiation with the peer connection on the home client in order to
    alter the transformation that it is applying to the home client's video
    source. Such a change is <em class=3D"rfc2119">NOT REQUIRED<!---0.03293=
0%--></em> to change anything related to sink A
    or B or the home client's video source.</p>
    <p>Note that this specification does not define a mechanism by which a
    change to the remote client's video source could automatically trigger =
a
    change to the home client's video source. Implementations may choose to
    make such source-to-sink optimizations as long as they only do so withi=
n
    the constraints established by the application, as the next example
    demonstrates.</p>
    <p>It is fairly obvious that changes to a given source will impact sink
    consumers. However, in some situations changes to a given sink may also
    cause implementations to adjust a source's settings. This is illustrate=
d in
    the following figures. In the first figure below, the home client's vid=
eo
    source is sending a video stream sized at 1920 by 1200 pixels. The vide=
o
    source is also unconstrained, such that the exact source dimensions are
    flexible as far as the application is concerned. Two
    <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL_" data-link-type=3D"idl" data-lt=3D"MediaStre=
am" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dom-mediastream" class=
=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dom-mediastream-58"><code>MediaStream<!---0.=
032930%--></code></a><!---0.032930%--> objects contain tracks with the same
    <!---0.032930%--><a data-link-type=3D"idl" data-xref-type=3D"attribute|=
dict-member|const" data-link-for=3D"MediaStreamTrack" data-xref-for=3D"Medi=
aStreamTrack" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-deviceid=
" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-deviceid-2"><code>deviceId<!---0.=
032930%--></code></a><!---0.032930%-->, and those <a data-xref-type=3D"_IDL=
_" data-link-type=3D"idl" data-lt=3D"MediaStream" href=3D"https://w3c.githu=
b.io/mediacapture-main/#dom-mediastream" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-fo=
r-dom-mediastream-59"><code>MediaStream<!---0.032930%--></code></a><!---0.0=
32930%-->s
    are connected to two different <code>&lt;<code><a data-xref-type=3D"ele=
ment" data-link-type=3D"element" data-cite=3D"html" data-cite-path=3D"/medi=
a.html" data-cite-frag=3D"video" href=3D"https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multi=
page/media.html#video">video<!---0.032930%--></a></code>&gt;</code> element=
 sinks A
    and B. Sink A has been sized to <code>width=3D"1920"</code> and
    <code>height=3D"1200"</code> and is displaying the source's video conte=
nt
    without any transformations. Sink B has been sized smaller and, as a
    result, is scaling the video down to fit its rectangle of 320 pixels ac=
ross
    by 200 pixels down.</p><img alt=3D"Changing media stream sinks may affe=
ct sources: before the requested change" src=3D"https://w3c.github.io/media=
capture-main/images/change_states_before2.svg" width=3D"800" height=3D"265"=
>
    <p>When the application changes sink A to a smaller dimension (from 192=
0 to
    1024 pixels wide and from 1200 to 768 pixels tall), the <a data-link-ty=
pe=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn=
-user-agent" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-user-agent-44">User Ag=
ent<!---0.032930%--></a>'s media
    pipeline may recognize that none of its sinks require the higher source
    resolution, and needless work is being done both on the part of the sou=
rce
    and sink A. In such a case and without any other constraints forcing th=
e
    source to continue producing the higher resolution video, the media
    pipeline <em class=3D"rfc2119">MAY<!---0.032930%--></em> change the sou=
rce resolution:</p><img alt=3D"Changing media stream sinks may affect sourc=
es: after the requested change" src=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-m=
ain/images/change_states_after2.svg">
    <p>In the above figure, the home client's video source resolution was
    changed to the greater of that from sink A and B in order to optimize
    playback. While not shown above, the same behavior could apply to peer
    connections and other sinks.</p>
    <p>It is possible that <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-ma=
in/#dom-constraints" class=3D"internalDFN" data-link-type=3D"idl" id=3D"ref=
-for-dom-constraints-3">constraints</a> can be applied to a track which a
    source is unable to satisfy, either because the source itself cannot
    satisfy the constraint or because the source is already satisfying a
    conflicting constraint. When this happens, the promise returned from
    <!---0.032930%--><a data-link-type=3D"idl" data-xref-type=3D"method" da=
ta-link-for=3D"MediaStreamTrack" data-xref-for=3D"MediaStreamTrack" data-lt=
=3D"applyConstraints()" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#do=
m-mediastreamtrack-applyconstraints" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-do=
m-mediastreamtrack-applyconstraints-6"><code>applyConstraints<!---0.032930%=
--></code></a><code>(<!---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%-->)</=
code><!---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%-->
    will be <a data-cite=3D"webidl" data-cite-path=3D"" data-cite-frag=3D"r=
eject" data-link-type=3D"dfn" href=3D"https://webidl.spec.whatwg.org/#rejec=
t">rejected</a>, without applying any of the new constraints. Since
    no change in constraints occurs in this case, there is also no required
    change to the source itself as a result of this condition. Here is an
    example of this behavior.</p>
    <p>In this example, two media streams each have a video track that shar=
e
    the same source. The first track initially has no constraints applied. =
It
    is connected to sink N. Sink N has a resolution of 800 by 600 pixels an=
d is
    scaling down the source's resolution of 1024 by 768 to fit. The other t=
rack
    has a <a data-lt=3D"required constraints" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io=
/mediacapture-main/#dfn-required-constraints" class=3D"internalDFN" data-li=
nk-type=3D"dfn" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-required-constraints-2">required constrai=
nt</a> forcing off
    the source's fill light; it is connected to sink P. Sink P has a width =
and
    height equal to that of the source.</p>
    <p><img alt=3D"Overconstrained application" src=3D"https://w3c.github.i=
o/mediacapture-main/images/overconstrained_apply.svg"></p>
    <p>Now, the first track adds a
    <a data-lt=3D"required constraints" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/media=
capture-main/#dfn-required-constraints" class=3D"internalDFN" data-link-typ=
e=3D"dfn" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-required-constraints-3">required constraint</a>=
 that the fill light
    should be forced on. At this point, both <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.=
io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-required-constraints" class=3D"internalDFN" data-=
link-type=3D"dfn" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-required-constraints-4">required constr=
aints</a> cannot be
    satisfied by the source (the fill light cannot be simultaneously on and=
 off
    at the same time). Since this state was caused by the first track's att=
empt
    to apply a conflicting constraint, the constraint application fails and
    there is no change in the source's settings nor to the constraints on
    either track.</p>
  </section>
