      </div>
    <p>The ordering of advanced ConstraintSets is significant. In the prece=
ding
    example it is impossible to satisfy both the 1920x1280 ConstraintSet an=
d
    the 4x3 aspect ratio ConstraintSet at the same time. Since the 1920x128=
0
    occurs first in the list, the <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" hre=
f=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-user-agent" class=3D"inte=
rnalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-user-agent-112">User Agent<!---0.032930%--></a> =
will attempt to satisfy it first.
    Application authors can therefore implement a backoff strategy by
    specifying multiple advanced ConstraintSets for the same property. The
    application also specifies two more advanced ConstraintSets, the
    first asking for a frame rate greater than 50, the second asking for a
    frame rate greater than 40.
    If the <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"https://w3c.github=
.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-user-agent" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-=
dfn-user-agent-113">User Agent<!---0.032930%--></a> is capable of setting a=
 frame rate greater than 50, it
    will (and the subsequent ConstraintSet will be trivially satisfied).
    However, if the <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"https://w=
3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-user-agent" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D=
"ref-for-dfn-user-agent-114">User Agent<!---0.032930%--></a> cannot set the=
 frame rate above 50, it will
    skip that ConstraintSet and attempt to set the frame rate above 40.
    In case the <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"https://w3c.g=
ithub.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-user-agent" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref=
-for-dfn-user-agent-115">User Agent<!---0.032930%--></a> cannot satisfy eit=
her of the two ConstraintSets, the
    'min' value in the basic ConstraintSet insists on 30 as a lower bound.
    In other words, the <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"https=
://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-user-agent" class=3D"internalDFN" i=
d=3D"ref-for-dfn-user-agent-116">User Agent<!---0.032930%--></a> would fail=
 altogether if it couldn't get a
    value over 30, but would choose a value over 50 if possible, then try f=
or
    a value over 40.</p>
    <p>Note that, unlike basic constraints, the constraints within a
    ConstraintSet in the advanced list must be satisfied together or skippe=
d
    together. Thus, {width: 1920, height: 1280} is a request for that speci=
fic
    resolution, not a request for that width or that height. One can think =
of
    the basic constraints as requesting an 'or' (non-exclusive) of the
    individual constraints, while each advanced ConstraintSet is requesting=
 an
    'and' of the individual constraints in the ConstraintSet. An applicatio=
n
    may inspect the full set of Constraints currently in effect via the
    <code>getConstraints()</code> accessor.</p>
    <p>The specific value that the <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" hr=
ef=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-user-agent" class=3D"int=
ernalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-user-agent-117">User Agent<!---0.032930%--></a>=
 chooses for a constrainable
    property is referred to as a Setting. For example, if the application
    applies a ConstraintSet specifying that the frameRate must be at least =
30
    frames per second, and no greater than 40, the Setting can be any
    intermediate value, e.g., 32, 35, or 37 frames per second. The applicat=
ion
    can query the current settings of the object's constrainable properties=
 via
    the <!---0.032930%--><a data-link-type=3D"idl" data-xref-type=3D"method=
" data-link-for=3D"MediaStreamTrack" data-xref-for=3D"MediaStreamTrack" dat=
a-lt=3D"getSettings()" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dom=
-mediastreamtrack-getsettings" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dom-medi=
astreamtrack-getsettings-4"><code>getSettings<!---0.032930%--></code></a><c=
ode>(<!---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%--><!---0.032930%-->)</code><!---0.0329=
30%--><!---0.032930%-->
    accessor.</p>
    <section id=3D"interface-definition-0"><div class=3D"header-wrapper"><h=
3 id=3D"x11-1-interface-definition"><bdi class=3D"secno">11.1<!---0.032930%=
--> </bdi>Interface Definition</h3><a class=3D"self-link" href=3D"https://w=
3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#interface-definition-0" aria-label=3D"Perma=
link for Section 11.1"></a></div>
     =20
      <p>Although this specification formally defines
      <dfn data-export=3D"" data-dfn-type=3D"interface" id=3D"dom-constrain=
ablepattern" data-idl=3D"interface" data-title=3D"ConstrainablePattern" dat=
a-dfn-for=3D"" tabindex=3D"0" aria-haspopup=3D"dialog"><code>ConstrainableP=
attern</code></dfn> as a WebIDL interface, it is actually a
      template or pattern for other interfaces and cannot be inherited dire=
ctly
      since the return values of the methods need to be extended, something
      WebIDL cannot do. Thus, each interface that wishes to make use of the
      functionality defined here will have to provide its own copy of the
      WebIDL for the functions and interfaces given here. However it can re=
fer
      to the semantics defined here, which will not change. See <a href=3D"=
https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#media-stream-track-interface-defin=
ition">MediaStreamTrack Interface
      Definition</a> for an example of this.</p>
      <p>This pattern relies on the <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediac=
apture-main/#dfn-constrainable-object" class=3D"internalDFN" data-link-type=
=3D"dfn" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-constrainable-object-3">constrainable object</a>=
 defining three
      internal slots:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>A <dfn data-dfn-for=3D"constrainable object" data-idl=3D"" dat=
a-noexport=3D"" data-dfn-type=3D"attribute" id=3D"dfn-capabilities-0" tabin=
dex=3D"0" aria-haspopup=3D"dialog">[[Capabilities]]</dfn> internal slot, in=
itialized to a
          <code>Capabilities</code> dictionary describing the aggregate
          allowable values for each constrainable property exposed, as
          explained under
          <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dom-capabilit=
ies" id=3D"ref-for-dom-capabilities-2">Capabilities</a>, or an empty dictio=
nary
          if it has none.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>A <dfn data-dfn-for=3D"constrainable object" data-idl=3D"" dat=
a-noexport=3D"" data-dfn-type=3D"attribute" id=3D"dfn-constraints" tabindex=
=3D"0" aria-haspopup=3D"dialog">[[Constraints]]</dfn> internal slot, initia=
lized to an
          empty <code>Constraints</code> dictionary.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>A <dfn data-dfn-for=3D"constrainable object" data-idl=3D"" dat=
a-noexport=3D"" data-dfn-type=3D"attribute" id=3D"dfn-settings-0" tabindex=
=3D"0" aria-haspopup=3D"dialog">[[Settings]]</dfn> internal slot, initializ=
ed to a
          <code>Settings</code> dictionary describing the currently active
          settings values for each constrainable property exposed, as
          explained under <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-mai=
n/#dom-settings" id=3D"ref-for-dom-settings-1">Settings</a>, or an empty
          dictionary if it has none.</p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <div>
      <div class=3D"example">Template:
        <pre class=3D"idl def" id=3D"webidl-396517552"><span class=3D"idlHe=
ader"><a class=3D"self-link" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-mai=
n/#webidl-396517552">WebIDL</a><button title=3D"Copy IDL to clipboard" clas=
