     =20
      <p>The syntax for the specification of the set of valid inputs depend=
s on
      the type of the values. In addition to the standard atomic types
      (boolean, long, double, DOMString), valid values include lists of any=
 of
      the atomic types, plus min-max ranges, as defined below.</p>
      <p>List values <em class=3D"rfc2119">MUST<!---0.032930%--></em> be in=
terpreted as disjunctions. For example, if a
      property 'facingMode' for a camera is defined as having valid values
      ["left", "right", "user", "environment"], this means that 'facingMode=
'
      can have the values "left", "right", "environment", and "user". Simil=
arly
      <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dom-constraints" =
class=3D"internalDFN" data-link-type=3D"idl" id=3D"ref-for-dom-constraints-=
9"><code>Constraints</code></a> restricting 'facingMode' to ["user", "left"=
, "right"]
      would mean that the <a data-link-type=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"htt=
ps://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn-user-agent" class=3D"internalDFN"=
 id=3D"ref-for-dfn-user-agent-131">User Agent<!---0.032930%--></a> should s=
elect a camera (or point the
      camera, if that is possible) so that "facingMode" is either "user",
      "left", or "right". This Constraint would thus request that the camer=
a
      not be facing away from the user, but would allow the <a data-link-ty=
pe=3D"dfn|abstract-op" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/mediacapture-main/#dfn=
-user-agent" class=3D"internalDFN" id=3D"ref-for-dfn-user-agent-132">User A=
gent<!---0.032930%--></a> to allow
      the user to choose other directions.</p>
